bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: Edward Haertel earned a B.A. in mathematics from the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and a Ph.D. in Education from the University of Chicago. In 1980, Haertel joined the faculty at the Stanford Graduate School of Education as an assistant professor. Since then, he has served as associate professor, Associate Dean for Facutly Affairs, and is now the Jacks Family Professor of Education, Emeritus.

Haertel's research centers on policy uses of achievement test data; the measurement of school learning; statistical issues in testing and accountability systems; and the impact of testing on curriculum and instruction. He has been closely involved in the creation and maintenance of California's school accountability system, and has served on advisory committees for other states and for testing companies.

Haertel has served as president of the National Council on Measurement in Education (1998-99), as a member of the National Assessment Governing Board (1997-2003), and as a member of the joint committee for 1999 edition of the Standards for Educational and Psychological Testing (1994-1999). He was a Fellow at the Center for Advanced Study in the Behavioral Sciences (1994-95) and is a Fellow of the American Psychological Association and currently vice president of the National Academy of Education.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The materials consist of Haertel's correspondence and memoranda, chronological files, and some teaching files.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Much of the material relates to Haertel's service on the National Assessment Governing Board (NAGB), which oversees the National Assessment of Educational Progress (NAEP). There is also material related to his service on the NAEP Technical Review Panel (TRP), which has done many small studies of various issues related to NAEP. Much of the material centers on controversies around NAGB’s procedures for establishing cut scores defining achievement levels (Basic, Proficient, Advanced) on the various NAEP tests. There is also some material dating to Haertel's time as a Fellow of the American Statistical Association and the American Educational Research Association, working at the National Center for Education Statistics (NCES) in Washington, DC on possible redesigns of national education data indicator systems. As part of that work, they collected some documents from earlier redesign discussions.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Much of this material dates from Haertel's service as Associate Dean for Faculty Affairs, but there’s also documents related to various efforts at defining course sequences and requirements for doctoral training in quantitative research methods. Other folders document deliberations leading to the closure of our counseling psychology program some years ago. Materials also document Haertel's involvement in a controversy over standard setting in the Commonwealth of Kentucky some years ago.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Includes material on the ill-fated California Learning Assessment System (CLAS), including some actual test materials used in the early 1990s when CLAS was being piloted. TAlso includes material from Haertel's service as director and as president of the National Council on Measurement in Education (NCME), material related to the LGBT special interest group of AERA, and a few documents from early in the history of the National Board for Professional Teaching Standards.
